@bstrie: Opened #25872.

@nagisa: If you `SIG_IGN` something other than `SIGPIPE`, then yes, there's currently no way to reset that. If you set a signal-handling function, UNIX resets it to `SIG_DFL` on exec. There should eventually be a way to un-ignore signals before exec, but I think it's less urgent. I don't think that there's a strong use case for ignoring any signal other than `SIGPIPE` in the current process only. Of the terminate-by-default signals, most are things like `SIGSEGV` where you can't ignore them, or things like `SIGHUP` that are generally sent to the entire process _group_ (so you want behavior to be inherited). Besides those two groups, the rest, other than `SIGPIPE`, appear to not be automatically generated (`SIGUSR1`, `SIGUSR2`, `SIGPIPE`, `SIGIO`, etc.), so you don't even get them in the first place unless you specifically want them. So I doubt anyone will be needing this badly in the immediate future, although yes, the functionality should exist at some point.

(BTW, current status of this PR is that I _just_ got an Android build working locally, and I'm trying to figure out why the buildbot is unhappy.)
